<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1863-02-02T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1863-02-02T00:00:00-05:00" n="455" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d455">
                        <head><persName type="from">Mr. Seward</persName> to <persName type="to">Mr.
                                Morris</persName></head>
                        <opener>
                            <seg rendition="#left">No. 51.]</seg>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>, <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>,</placeName>
                                <date calendar="gregorian" when="1863-02-02"><hi rend="italic">February</hi> 2, 1863.</date></dateline></opener>
                        <p><hi rend="smallcaps">Sir:</hi> I have the pleasure to enclose herewith a
                            transcript of a letter of the 20th ultimo, addressed to this department
                            by the secretary of the American Board of Commissioners for Foreign
                            Missions at Boston, on the subject of your successful exertions to bring
                            to punishment the assassins of the Rev. Mr. Merriam.</p>
                        <p>I am, sir, your obedient servant,</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>WILLIAM H. SEWARD.</signed></closer>
                        <postscript>
                            <p>E. <hi rend="smallcaps">Joy Morris</hi>, Esq., <hi rend="italic">&amp;c., &amp;c., &amp;c., Constantinople.</hi></p>
                        </postscript>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>